{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2306b718-6690-4a5e-aa32-c82b4bb19508","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the `webapi` template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n**Authentication options** (via `--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C |\n| `SingleOrg` | Azure AD (single tenant) |\n| `MultiOrg` | Azure AD (multi-tenant) |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Example with auth:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer or cookie auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` or use ASP.NET Core Identity for local accounts.\n\nWould you like help scaffolding a specific configuration?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2ffec11f-6752-4d09-a5f4-48c766c81491","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context mentions dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":290,"requestId":"401B:3AA73:5B4B462:63C4BA4:69F00422"},"id":"61270a45-6418-429a-9a38-85c86c52ddd0","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:49:45.707Z","parentId":"279ac90d-a28a-4681-bdb7-1648dba8a457"}
